PK for prior auth data
The patients date of birth, typically used to calculate the patients age and ensure eligibility for age-related benefits.
The patients full legal name, including first, middle, and last names.
A classification that indicates the type of healthcare plan the patient is enrolled in, such as commercial, Medicaid, or Medicare.
The name of the healthcare product or insurance plan that the patient is enrolled in.
A unique identifier for the prior authorization request.
The line number or entry within the prior authorization request, typically used to track specific items or services.
The date on which the prior authorization request was received by the insurance provider or healthcare entity.
The date on which the healthcare provider or payer responded to the prior authorization request.
The date from which the authorized services or treatments will begin.
The date when the authorized services or treatments will end.
A classification indicating the urgency of the prior authorization request (e.g., urgent, routine).
A classification of the type of authorization (e.g., IP Admit, Outpatient, Concurrent, Retrospective, etc.)
The classification of the type of service being requested (e.g., surgery, diagnostic testing, therapy).
The method by which the prior authorization was reviewed (e.g., manual, auto-approved, etc.).
The ICD procedure code that represents a specific medical procedure or service being requested for prior authorization.
A description of the procedure or service that corresponds to the procedure code.
The CPT4 procedure code that represents a specific medical procedure or service being requested for prior authorization.
A description of the procedure or service that corresponds to the procedure code.
The code indicating the setting in which the requested service will be provided (e.g., outpatient, inpatient, office).
A description of the setting where the service will be provided, corresponding to the place of service code.
The number of units (e.g., sessions, days, doses) of the service requested in the prior authorization.
The number of units (e.g., sessions, days, doses) of the service that were approved in the prior authorization.
The number of units (e.g., sessions, days, doses) of the service that were denied in the prior authorization.
The primary diagnosis code for the member, typically provided using the ICD-10 coding system.
A description of the primary diagnosis code, explaining the medical condition or reason for the requested services.
The current status of the prior authorization request (e.g., approved, denied, pending).
A code that explains the reason why a prior authorization request was denied (e.g., coverage limitations, lack of medical necessity).
The clinical reasoning or notes provided to justify the need for the requested service or procedure, often included as part of the clinical review.
A flag indicating whether an appeal has been filed for a denied prior authorization (Y = Yes, N = No).
The current status of the appeal process for a prior authorization request (e.g., under review, approved, denied).
The result of the appeal process for the prior authorization (e.g., granted, overturned, denied).
The full name of the individual(s) who reviewed the prior authorization request and made the determination.
The title or position of the individual(s) who reviewed the prior authorization request (e.g., nurse, pharmacist, physician, reviewer).
A flag indicating whether the review process for the prior authorization was delegated to an external party (Y = Yes, N = No).
The name of the entity that was delegated the responsibility of reviewing the prior authorization request (e.g., third-party vendor name, outsourced entity name).
The name of the provider group that submitted the prior authorization request.
The full name of the individual provider who submitted the prior authorization request.
The Taxpayer Identification Number (TIN) of the requesting provider, used for tax and billing purposes.
The National Provider Identifier (NPI) number assigned to the requesting healthcare provider, used for identification in the healthcare system.
The network status of the requesting provider, indicating whether they are in-network or out-of-network for the patients health plan.
The specialty of the requesting provider (e.g., cardiology, dermatology, orthopedics), indicating their area of expertise.
The version of the ICD codeset used in the prior authorization.
The secondary diagnosis code for the member, typically provided using the ICD-10 coding system.
A description of the secondary diagnosis code, explaining the medical condition or reason for the requested services.
The age of the patient.

PK for prior auth data
The average cost incurred by the health plan to review and approve a prior authorization request automatically.
The average cost incurred to have a nurse review and assess a prior authorization request.
The average cost incurred to have a medical doctor (MD) review a prior authorization request.
The average cost incurred to have a Pharmacist review a prior authorization request.
The average cost incurred to have an administrative staff member review a prior authorization request.
The average cost incurred to have a nurse review and assess a clinical appeal.
The average cost incurred to have a medical doctor (MD) review and assess a clinical appeal.
The average cost incurred to have a Pharmacist review and assess a clinical appeal.
The average number of prior authorizations (PAs) a nurse can review in one hour.
The average number of prior authorizations (PAs) a medical doctor (MD) can review in one hour.
The average number of prior authorizations (PAs) a Pharmacist can review in one hour.
The average number of prior authorizations (PAs) an administrative staff member can review in one hour.
The percentage of prior authorization requests that are approved by the health plan or payer.
The percentage of prior authorization requests that are denied by the health plan or payer.
The percentage of denied prior authorizations that are appealed by the provider or member.
The percentage of appeals that result in an overturned decision (denial reversed and authorization granted).
